Based on the alarm sequence and the long-run PS traffic scenario, this looks more like a shared storage / filesystem I/O stall affecting CMP and DMP rather than an application crash.

Key observations:

dmp disk-access-fail occurred first at 08:13:11

Then both:

CMP[0]/SHARED

CMP[1]/SHARED


Afterwards:

CMP[1]/LOG


PM collection also failed later (PM DATA COLLECTION FAIL)

No pod restart occurred:

all pods still Running

RESTARTS = 0



This strongly indicates:

containers stayed alive,

but disk I/O temporarily became unavailable or blocked.


Possible root causes

1. Shared PVC / storage backend latency (Most probable)

Since both CMP instances reported:

/SHARED

nearly same timestamp,


the common dependency is likely:

RWX shared volume,

NFS,

CephFS,

Gluster,

or hostPath backed shared storage.


Under heavy:

30 real UE PS calls

600 TM500 FTP sessions

cell reselection every minute


there may be:

excessive PM/log/database writes,

inode exhaustion,

NFS timeout,

storage latency spike,

fs freeze.


The DMP DB alarm before CMP alarms supports this sequence: DB write stall -> shared filesystem inaccessible -> CMP logging failure


